### **Conclusion**
The story of King Wu Hou and Wu Qi reflects a **universal cautionary tale** about the pitfalls of unchecked self-confidence in leadership. Western thought, from ancient Greek philosophy to modern political theory, repeatedly warns against the same dangers—whether through the lens of **tyranny, hubris, or the necessity of humility**. The passage’s moral—that a ruler must balance self-assurance with openness to critique—resonates deeply in both Eastern and Western traditions as a cornerstone of wise governance. [end of text]


